  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": "{\"id\": \"https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad\", \"type\": \"ContextOfUse\", \"name\": \"COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)\", \"description\": \"A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment.\", \"deviceClass\": \"Class III\", \"modelInfluence\": \"High\", \"decisionConsequence\": \"High\", \"intendedUse\": \"Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.\", \"hasOperatingEnvelope\": {\"id\": \"https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad/envelope-bounded\", \"type\": \"OperatingEnvelope\", \"name\": \"Bounded VAD operating envelope — flow, speed, hematocrit, temperature, pressure\", \"description\": \"Volumetric flow rate: 1–7 L/min (nominal 4 L/min ±0.05 L/min measurement uncertainty). Impeller rotational speed: 2 000–4 500 RPM (±10 RPM). Inlet hematocrit: 35–45 % (±1 %). Blood temperature: 36–38 °C (±0.2 °C). Mean outlet pressure: 60–120 mmHg (±2 mmHg). Geometry tolerance on impeller tip clearance: 150–250 µm. All 25 experimental validation operating points lie within these bounds; no extrapolation beyond the envelope is claimed.\"}, \"hasApplicabilityConstraint\": {\"id\": \"https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad/applicability-bounded\", \"type\": \"ApplicabilityConstraint\", \"name\": \"Applicability constraint — FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, Newtonian blood surrogate, steady-state hemolysis index\", \"description\": \"Model applicability is restricted to: (1) the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry (as specified in FDA 2012 benchmark); (2) Newtonian blood surrogate (viscosity 0.0035 Pa·s, density 1 060 kg/m³); (3) steady-state or time-averaged hemolysis index QoI only — transient hemolysis spikes are out of scope; (4) single-pass exposure durations up to 120 s. Application to other pump geometries, non-Newtonian rheology regimes, or multi-pass recirculation scenarios requires separate credibility assessment.\"}}}",
